# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 82ND LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 82ND DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — MODULA-3 (DEC SRC + Olivetti +
# Critical Mass, 1988-present) — and its FIRST documented Modula-3
# CLI mechanism: stdlib `Arg.Pop()` argv-stack interface + CASE-on-
# character dispatch in Makefile.m3.
# Taxonomy now spans 336 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 82 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R594 Rust=56 fern/bita → R595 Go=56
# uiprogress/mysql_random_data_load → R596 TS-Node=56 ora/create-fuels)
# followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R597 Modula-3 THIS).  Leaderboard
# unchanged: Rust=56, Go=56, TypeScript-Node=56 (three-way tie at 56
# since R596).
#
# Modula-3 is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being
# the DEC SRC + OLIVETTI SUCCESSOR-TO-MODULA-2 with proper objects +
# garbage collection + exceptions + threads as language features.
# The Wirth lineage and the DEC SRC lineage DIVERGED at Modula-2:
#   - Niklaus Wirth (ETH Zurich) went MINIMALIST: Oberon (1987) →
#     Oberon-2 (1991) → Oberon-07 (2007)
#   - DEC SRC + Olivetti went FEATURE-FULL: Modula-3 (1988) with
#     objects + GC + threads + exceptions + generics + isolation
# Modula-3 directly influenced Java (Bill Joy + James Gosling
# acknowledged Modula-3 as a design source for Java 1.0's
# interfaces, generics, GC integration, and lightweight threads).
# Microsoft's C# also borrowed Modula-3 ideas via Cardelli's
# influence at MS Research.
#
# The taxonomy now documents the COMPLETE Pascal lineage:
#   Pascal (1970) → Modula-2 (1978, MOCKA R???) →
#                 ├── Wirth branch: Oberon-2 (1991, voc R565)
#                 └── DEC SRC branch: Modula-3 (1988, cm3 R597 THIS)
#   Eiffel (1985, se R573) — parallel Pascal-influenced OOP branch
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS MODULA-3 AND WHY IS IT THE 82ND LANGUAGE?
#
# Modula-3 is a strongly-typed, garbage-collected, object-oriented
# programming language designed by a group at DEC SRC + Olivetti
# Research 1986-1989 with the goal of being a STRICT EVOLUTION of
# Modula-2 that added the features needed for production systems
# programming.  Distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FULL OBJECT-ORIENTED SUPPORT — Modula-3 has CLASSES with
#      single inheritance + multiple INTERFACE implementations
#      (predating Java's interface model by 7 years):
#
#          INTERFACE Drawable;
#            TYPE T <: ROOT;  (* abstract subtype of ROOT *)
#            PROCEDURE Draw (self: T; canvas: Canvas.T);
#          END Drawable.
#
#          MODULE Drawable;
#            REVEAL T = ROOT BRANDED OBJECT
#              x, y: INTEGER;
#            METHODS
#              Draw (canvas: Canvas.T) := DefaultDraw;
#            END;
#          END Drawable.
#
#      Compare:
#         * Modula-2: NO objects (records + procedures only)
#         * Oberon-2: TYPE-BOUND PROCEDURES (methods) but no
#                     formal interfaces
#         * Eiffel: classes + multiple inheritance with rename/
#                    redefine/undefine/select
#         * Java: classes + interfaces (1995, INFLUENCED BY
#                  Modula-3)
#         * Modula-3: CLASS + REVEAL hierarchy for opaque types
#                      + multiple interfaces (1988, PREDATES
#                      Java by 7 years)
#      FIRST documented language with class + interface + opaque-
#      type-revealing system that directly influenced Java's
#      interface design.
#
#   2. GARBAGE COLLECTION IN LANGUAGE — Modula-3 specifies a
#      CONSERVATIVE GARBAGE COLLECTOR as part of the language.
#      All HEAP-allocated objects are GC-managed; manual memory
#      management is RESTRICTED to UNSAFE modules:
#
#          MODULE Main;
#          IMPORT IO;
#            TYPE T = REF RECORD value: INTEGER; END;
#            VAR p: T;
#          BEGIN
#            p := NEW(T);    (* GC-allocated *)
#            p.value := 42;
#            (* p is unreferenced after this scope — GC reclaims *)
#          END Main.
#
#      Compare:
#         * Modula-2: no GC (manual heap management via stdlib)
#         * Oberon-2: GC (similar to Modula-3 here)
#         * Eiffel: GC
#         * Java: GC (INFLUENCED BY Modula-3)
#         * Modula-3: GC + UNSAFE keyword for restricted manual
#                      management
#      FIRST mainstream-trajectory language with garbage
#      collection as language specification (predating Java
#      by 7 years).
#
#   3. UNSAFE INTERFACES — Modula-3 introduces the UNSAFE
#      keyword for modules that need raw pointer access or
#      direct memory manipulation:
#
#          UNSAFE INTERFACE LowLevel;
#            PROCEDURE GetWord(addr: ADDRESS): WORD;
#            PROCEDURE PutWord(addr: ADDRESS; value: WORD);
#          END LowLevel.
#
#      Importing modules that USE LowLevel must ALSO declare
#      themselves UNSAFE.  This creates an explicit boundary
#      between safe + unsafe code.  Compare:
#         * Rust: `unsafe { ... }` blocks (2014+) — directly
#                  influenced by Modula-3's UNSAFE
#         * C#: `unsafe` keyword
#         * Java: no unsafe escape hatch (JNI required)
#         * Modula-3: UNSAFE INTERFACE/MODULE (1988, PREDATES
#                      Rust's unsafe by 26 years)
#      FIRST documented language with formal UNSAFE/SAFE
#      isolation at the module level.
#
#   4. THREADS + EXCEPTIONS IN STANDARD LIBRARY — Modula-3
#      introduced THREADS + EXCEPTIONS as core language
#      features (Modula-2 had neither):
#
#          (* Threads: *)
#          IMPORT Thread;
#          TYPE Closure = Thread.SizedClosure OBJECT
#              METHODS apply(): REFANY;
#            END;
#          VAR t := Thread.Fork(NEW(MyClosure));
#          ...
#          EVAL Thread.Join(t);
#
#          (* Exceptions: *)
#          EXCEPTION DivByZero;
#          PROCEDURE Divide (a, b: REAL): REAL RAISES {DivByZero} =
#            BEGIN
#              IF b = 0.0 THEN RAISE DivByZero END;
#              RETURN a / b;
#            END Divide;
#
#          TRY
#            x := Divide(1.0, 0.0);
#          EXCEPT
#            DivByZero => IO.Put("division by zero")
#          END;
#
#      Compare:
#         * Modula-2: no threads, no exceptions
#         * Java: threads + exceptions (1995, INFLUENCED BY
#                  Modula-3)
#         * C++: exceptions but no language-level threads until
#                 C++11
#         * Modula-3: THREADS + EXCEPTIONS in core language
#                      since 1988
#      FIRST documented language with threads + exceptions as
#      core language features predating Java.
#
#   5. GENERICS — Modula-3 had GENERIC INTERFACES + GENERIC
#      MODULES (parametric polymorphism) since 1988:
#
#          GENERIC INTERFACE Sequence (Element);
#            TYPE T <: SequencePublic;
#            PROCEDURE New (): T;
#            PROCEDURE AddHi (s: T; READONLY x: Element.T);
#            PROCEDURE Size (s: T): INTEGER;
#          END Sequence.
#
#          GENERIC MODULE Sequence (Element);
#            ... implementation parameterized by Element module
#          END Sequence.
#
#          (* Instantiate: *)
#          MODULE IntSeq = Sequence(Integer) END IntSeq.
#
#      Compare:
#         * Modula-2: no generics
#         * Ada: generics since 1980 (similar idea)
#         * Java: generics added Java 5 (2004, 16 years after
#                  Modula-3)
#         * C++: templates (1985+, similar idea)
#         * Modula-3: GENERIC INTERFACE/MODULE since 1988 with
#                      MODULE-AS-TYPE-PARAMETER semantics
#      FIRST documented language with module-as-type-parameter
#      generics (Java's generics arrived 16 years later).
#
#   6. DEC SRC LINEAGE — Modula-3 came from the SAME RESEARCH
#      LAB that produced foundational systems work:
#         * DEC SRC Modula-3 (1988-1995)
#         * DEC SRC's Topaz operating system (Modula-3-written)
#         * DEC SRC's Vesta source-control system
#         * Spin operating system (UW + DEC SRC, Modula-3-written)
#         * Conjuror network protocols
#         * The PRESS publishing system
#      Many DEC SRC alumni went on to define modern systems
#      research: Greg Nelson → ESC/Java + Simplify SMT prover;
#      Luca Cardelli → Microsoft Research (foundations of CLR,
#      F#, C#); Bill Kalsow → Critical Mass + many Modula-3
#      tools.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
